Introduction¶

My objective is to predict the day price direction of Tesla, Inc. (TSLA). The stock market is a highly complex and volatile environment. To achieve profitability, it's not necessary to predict the exact price of a stock, but rather its price direction: whether it will be higher or lower than it is today. For Tesla, this means predicting if the next day's closing price will be higher than the opening price. If we anticipate a rise, we might choose to buy some shares; if we foresee a decline, selling might be the better option. Thus, the goal is a binary classification to determine whether the next day's closing price for Tesla will be higher than its opening price.

Here, I have daily historical data for the period from 2010 up to the year 2024 that I have split into training (2010-2020), validation (2020-2022) and testing (2022-2024) periods. The data is available in the TSLA_train.csv, TSLA_val.csv and AMZN_test.csv files, respectively.

Additionally, I will plot the variables to identify any trends and investigate the potential for engineering additional features. def analyse(dataframe):
    """Runs an exploration analysis of the dataframe."""
    print("Shape", dataframe.shape, "\n")
    print("Columns", dataframe.columns, "\n")
    dataframe.info()
    print("\n", dataframe.describe(), "\n")
    print("The data ranges from", dataframe["Date"].min(), "to", dataframe["Date"].max())
    dataframe.plot(x="Date", y=["Close", "Open", "High", "Low"])

Once I have explored the data, I moved on to the predictive modeling phase. My objective is to predict whether the next day's closing price will be higher than the opening price. Since this information isn't explicitly available in the data, I need to infer it.

To do this, I first ensure the data is sorted by date using the sort_values method, passing in the Date column as a parameter and sorting it in ascending order.

Next, I will shift the DataFrame by one row (one day) to compare the prices. Pandas provides the shift method for this purpose, allowing me to shift the data from the next day back by specifying a period of minus one. Since this is a logical operation, Pandas will return a True/False result for each comparison. I will convert these to 1/0 for use in my machine learning models by mapping the results to integers. To store this information, I will create a new column called Target.

In [15]:
# make sure that our data is sorted by date
df_train.sort_values(by="Date", inplace=True)
df_val.sort_values(by="Date", inplace=True)
df_test.sort_values(by="Date", inplace=True)
In [16]:
# notice that I shift by a period of '-1', this takes the next day's price direction for the current day
# a positive period will take the days from the past
df_train["Target"] = (df_train["Close"] > df_train["Open"]).shift(periods=-1, fill_value=0).astype(int)

At this point, I can start building some machine learning models to predict the target variable. But, before I do that, it might be useful to engineer some additional features that may help me better predict the price direction. In the next section, I will explore some possibilities for doing feature engineering.

Stock prices are inherently time-dependent, with the next day's price influenced by prices and various other factors from previous days. To account for the values from the last n days and capture trends or the magnitude of price changes, I need to consider the historical data.

One simple approach is to calculate a moving average. In Pandas, the rolling method allows for sliding window calculations, making it easy to compute moving averages. By using this method, I can calculate the 3-day and 7-day moving averages and add them as features to the dataset.

Here's how it works: first, I ensure the data is sorted by date. If the data isn't sorted, the results from the rolling method would be invalid. With sorted data, I then use the rolling method to calculate the moving averages over the desired window lengths and add these values as new columns in the dataset. This process helps capture the underlying trends in the stock prices over time.

In [21]:
df_train["Moving_Average_3"] = (df_train["Close"] - df_train["Open"]).rolling(window=3, min_periods=1).mean()
df_val["Moving_Average_3"] = (df_val["Close"] - df_val["Open"]).rolling(window=3, min_periods=1).mean()
df_test["Moving_Average_3"] = (df_test["Close"] - df_test["Open"]).rolling(window=3, min_periods=1).mean()
In [22]:
df_train["Moving_Average_7"] = (df_train["Close"] - df_train["Open"]).rolling(window=7, min_periods=1).mean()
df_val["Moving_Average_7"] = (df_val["Close"] - df_val["Open"]).rolling(window=7, min_periods=1).mean()
df_test["Moving_Average_7"] = (df_test["Close"] - df_test["Open"]).rolling(window=7, min_periods=1).mean()

Feature engineering can be simpler, I can just take the current day's price direction or the price range. Anything that comes to mind, that can be considered to be useful, should be tested and tried.

Logistic Regression

Decision Tree

Random Forest

Logistic regression doesn't perform well for this problem. An AUC (Area Under the Curve) score of less than 0.5 indicates that the classifier is performing worse than random guessing. Considering the complexity of this task, any AUC score above 0.5 would be considered sufficient.

Random Forest¶

Now I will try to use many decision trees, i.e., a forest. Random forest is an ensemble model that builds multiple decision trees, each with a different (random) sub-set of attributes.

In [32]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=RANDOM_SEED)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
RocCurveDisplay.from_estimator(rf, X_val, y_val)
Out[32]:
<sklearn.metrics._plot.roc_curve.RocCurveDisplay at 0x17d1b3fa0>

As expected, the model does outperform the decision tree by 0.07, it actually performs very well.

Gradient Boosting Ensemble¶

The final ensemble technique I want to try is gradient boosting. This algorithm sets the stage for the next part, where I will explore a deep learning approach to solve the problem.

RocCurveDisplay.from_estimator(gb, X_val, y_val)

Contrary to our expectations, the gradient boosting classifier does not outperform previous models and scored 0.49 AUC. It performs actually the same as Logistic regression

I find out that random forest works best for this data set. In the next section, I will train a deep learning model with the aim to outperform the baseline set here, i.e., AUC = 0.52.

model = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=[X_train.shape[1],]),
    tf.keras.layers.Normalization(axis=-1),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation="relu", kernel_initializer='random_normal', bias_initializer='zeros'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2, seed=RANDOM_SEED),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(5, activation="relu", kernel_initializer='random_normal', bias_initializer='zeros'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid", kernel_initializer='random_normal', bias_initializer='zeros')
])

# this configures the model's loss function, weight optimizer, and metrics to keep track of
model.compile(
    loss="binary_crossentropy", 
    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(), 
    metrics=['AUC']
)

I am going to train my model for 50 epochs, and keep track of its loss (binary_crossentropy) and AUC values during each epoch.

To prevent overfitting, I am implementing two callbacks: (1) learning rate scheduler, and (2) early stopping callback.

In [38]:
def learning_rate_scheduler(epoch, learning_rate):
    """Learning rate decay callback."""
    if epoch < 5:
        return learning_rate
    else:
        return float(tf.keras.backend.get_value(learning_rate * tf.math.exp(-0.01)))

early_stopping_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=10, verbose=1, restore_best_weights=True)
learning_rate_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(learning_rate_scheduler)
In [39]:

history = model.fit(
    x=X_train,
    y=y_train,
    validation_data=(X_val, y_val),
    epochs=50,
    verbose=1,
    callbacks=[early_stopping_callback, learning_rate_callback])

Conclusion¶

The random forest provided the best AUC score on the validation set. It is a common machine learning practice to train multiple models on the same train/validation data set and provide a model that works best. To simulate a production environment, I have held the test set aside until now.

In the next cell, I am going to evaluate the performance of the random forest on the test set. This is simple as calling plot_roc_curve with the test set instead of the validation one.

As a bonus, in the last cell, I am showing a feature importance plot, which plots the importance of each feature in regard to the predictive performance of the model (the higher the value the more important the feature is for determining the value of the target variable).
